By: Delegate Guzzone
Introduced and read first time: February 12, 2026
Assigned to: Health
Committee Report: Favorable
House action: Adopted
Read second time: March 9, 2026
CHAPTER ______
1 AN ACT concerning
2 Residential Service Agencies – Private Duty Nursing – On–Site Nurse Training
3 Programs
4 FOR the purpose of requiring the Maryland Department of Health to adopt regulations
5 that authorize a residential service agency to provide training to a licensed nurse
6 after hire; authorizing a residential service agency that provides private duty
7 nursing services to employ a licensed nurse who does not meet certain requirements
8 under certain circumstances; requiring a residential service agency to provide
9 training and a competency evaluation for certain nurses; and generally relating to
10 residential service agencies.
11 BY repealing and reenacting, with amendments,
12 Article – Health – General
13 Section 19–4A–03
14 Annotated Code of Maryland
15 (2023 Replacement Volume and 2025 Supplement)
16 BY adding to
17 Article – Health – General
18 Section 19–4A–03.2
19 Annotated Code of Maryland
20 (2023 Replacement Volume and 2025 Supplement)
21 SECTION 1. BE IT ENACTED BY THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF MARYLAND,
22 That the Laws of Maryland read as follows:
EXPLANATION: CAPITALS INDICATE MATTER ADDED TO EXISTING LAW.
[Brackets] indicate matter deleted from existing law.
Underlining indicates amendments to bill.
Strike out indicates matter stricken from the bill by amendment or deleted from the law by
amendment. *hb1284*

2 HOUSE BILL 1284
1 Article – Health – General
2 19–4A–03.
3 (a) The Department shall adopt regulations that set standards for the care,
4 treatment, health, safety, welfare, and comfort of individuals who receive home health care
5 services through a residential service agency.
6 (b) The regulations shall provide for the licensing of residential service agencies.
7 (c) The regulations shall include provisions that:
8 (1) Provide for the establishment of residential service agencies;
9 (2) Establish qualifications for licensure;
10 (3) Set minimum standards for individuals who provide home health care
11 services through a residential service agency; [and]
12 (4) Require the residential service agency to screen and verify the
13 character references of all home health care providers that are employed by the residential
14 service agency; AND
15 (5) AUTHORIZE A RESIDENTIAL SERVICE AGENCY TO PROVIDE
16 TRAINING TO A LICENSED NURSE AFTER HIRE IN ACCORDANCE WITH § 19–4A–03.2
17 OF THIS SUBTITLE.
18 19–4A–03.2.
19 (A) A RESIDENTIAL SERVICE AGENCY THAT PROVIDES PRIVATE DUTY
20 NURSING SERVICES MAY EMPLOY A LICENSED NURSE WHO DOES NOT MEET THE
21 CLINICAL EXPERIENCE REQUIREMENTS ESTABLISHED BY THE DEPARTMENT IF THE
22 RESIDENTIAL SERVICE AGENCY PROVIDES TRAINING AND A COMPETENCY
23 EVALUATION IN ACCORDANCE WITH THIS SECTION.
24 (B) A RESIDENTIAL SERVICE AGENCY THAT SEEKS TO EMPLOY A NURSE
25 DESCRIBED UNDER SUBSECTION (A) OF THIS SECTION SHALL:
26 (1) ESTABLISH AND IMPLEMENT A TRAINING PROGRAM DESIGNED TO
27 ENSURE SAFE AND COMPETENT CARE BASED ON PATIENT NEEDS;
28 (2) ENSURE THE NURSE RECEIVES CLINICAL SUPERVISION BY A
29 REGISTERED NURSE QUALIFIED IN PRIVATE DUTY NURSING SERVICES;

HOUSE BILL 1284 3
1 (3) ASSIGN THE NURSE TO A QUALIFIED PRECEPTOR OR CLINICAL
2 SUPERVISOR UNTIL COMPETENCY IS DEMONSTRATED;
3 (4) DOCUMENT SATISFACTORY COMPLETION OF REQUIRED
4 COMPETENCY STANDARDS IN THE NURSE’S PERSONNEL FILE; AND
5 (5) CONDUCT COMPETENCY EVALUATIONS OF THE NURSE:
6 (I) ANNUALLY; OR
7 (II) FOR DISCIPLINARY PURPOSES, ON A MORE FREQUENT
8 SCHEDULE AS REQUIRED BY THE DEPARTMENT.
9 (C) A TRAINING PROGRAM AND COMPETENCY EVALUATION REQUIRED
10 UNDER THIS SECTION ARE SUBJECT TO APPROVAL BY THE DEPARTMENT.
11 (D) THIS SECTION MAY NOT BE CONSTRUED TO AFFECT REQUIREMENTS
12 RELATING TO OCCUPATIONAL LICENSURE, SCOPE OF PRACTICE, OR STANDARDS OF
13 CARE.
14 SECTION 2. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That this Act shall take effect
15 October 1, 2026.
Approved:
